          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Hungary-Russia ties</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto will attend the <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-peter-szijjarto-join-russia-syria-belarus-security-summit/" target="_blank">Minsk Conference on Eurasian Security</a>, joining Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov and Syrian Foreign Minister Bassam Sabbagh. The conference, promoted by the Russia-aligned CSTO, is positioned as an alternative to the <a href="https://securityconference.org/en/about-us/about-the-msc/" target="_blank">Munich Security Conference</a> and reflects Hungary’s deepening ties with Russia and Belarus.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Szijjarto’s participation highlights Hungary’s divergent stance within NATO, especially its ongoing cooperation with Moscow on energy and diplomatic fronts. Hungary has also been under scrutiny this week regarding Hungarian-Russian relations as PM Victor Orban made a visit to Tbilisi after the <a href="https://www.tbsnews.net/worldbiz/europe/georgias-election-fears-war-russia-overshadow-eu-hopes-voters-980011" target="_blank">controversial election</a> to congregate the Pro Russia Georgian Dream party and received massive boos (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FdZktmTCDEc" target="_blank">watch video</a>) from protestors. </p>
        </mj-text>
